  "prompt": "Indian Institutes of Technology (IITs): What is the fuss in IIT-M Periyar-Ambedkar study circle all about?",
  "response": "The IIT-M Periyar-Ambedkar Study Circle controversy primarily revolves around the group's activism and criticism by the institution's administration. The Periyar-Ambedkar Study Circle (PASC) is a student-run organization at IIT Madras named after social reformers Periyar E.V. Ramasamy and Dr. B.R. Ambedkar. The study circle engages in discussions about social issues, caste discrimination, and politics, often advocating for Dalit rights and social justice.\n\nThe controversy erupted in May 2015, when IIT Madras temporarily derecognized the PASC, citing complaints about the group's activities being political and potentially divisive. This action was seen by many as an attempt to suppress dissent and curb the freedom of expression. It sparked significant debate and backlash both within the institution and in the wider public sphere, leading to accusations of infringing on students' rights to organize and express critical viewpoints.\n\nCritics argued that the derecognition was a response to the group's vocal criticism of the government's policies, including issues related to caste and social inequality. The matter drew considerable attention and highlighted the tensions between academic freedom and administrative control within educational institutions. After substantial pressure and public scrutiny, IIT Madras eventually reinstated the Periyar-Ambedkar Study Circle.\n\nThe incident brought to light important questions about the role of student organizations in academic institutions, freedom of speech, and the broader issues of caste and social justice within Indian society.",
